# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-lake-formation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC is a method of implementing access control policies that is highly adaptable and can be customized using a wide range of attributes, making it suitable for use in distributed or rapidly changing environments.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The only limitations on the policies that can be implemented with ABAC are the capabilities of the computational language and the availability of relevant attributes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC policy rules are generated as Boolean functions of the subject's attributes, the object's attributes, and the environment attributes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Unlike role-based access control (RBAC), which defines roles that carry a specific set of privileges associated with them and to which subjects are assigned, ABAC can express complex rule sets that can evaluate many different attributes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Through defining consistent subject and object attributes into security policies, ABAC eliminates the need for explicit authorizations to individuals’ subjects needed in a non-ABAC access method, reducing the complexity of managing access lists and groups.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute values can be set-valued or atomic-valued.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Set-valued attributes contain more than one atomic value.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Atomic-valued attributes contain only one atomic value.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Examples are *clearance* and *sensitivity*.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be compared to static values or to one another, thus enabling relation-based access control.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control is sometimes referred to as **policy-based access control** (**PBAC**) or **claims-based access control** (**CBAC**), which is a Microsoft-specific term.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The key standards that implement ABAC are XACML and ALFA (XACML).
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP or Policy Decision Point is the brain of the architecture.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] This is the piece which evaluates incoming requests against policies it has been configured with.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The PIP or Policy Information Point bridges the PDP to external sources of attributes e.g.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be about anything and anyone.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Policies are statements that bring together attributes to express what can happen and is not allowed.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Policies in ABAC can be granting or denying policies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Policies can also be local or global and can be written in a way that they override other policies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] With ABAC you can have an unlimited number of policies that cater to many different scenarios and technologies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Historically, access control models have included mandatory access control (MAC), discretionary access control (DAC), and more recently role-based access control (RBAC).
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] These access control models are user-centric and do not take into account additional parameters such as resource information, the relationship between the user (the requesting entity) and the resource, and dynamic information, e.g. time of the day or user IP.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC tries to address this by defining access control based on attributes which describe the requesting entity (the user), the targeted object or resource, the desired action (view, edit, delete), and environmental or contextual information.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] This is why access control is said to be attribute-based.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] XACML, the eXtensible Access Control Markup Language, defines an architecture (shared with ALFA and NGAC), a policy language, and a request/response scheme.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] It does not handle attribute management (user attribute assignment, object attribute assignment, environment attribute assignment) which is left to traditional IAM tools, databases, and directories.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Companies, including every branch in the United States military, have started using ABAC.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] At a basic level, ABAC protects data with 'IF/THEN/AND' rules rather than assign data to users.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The US Department of Commerce has made this a mandatory practice and the adoption is spreading throughout several governmental and military agencies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The concept of ABAC can be applied at any level of the technology stack and an enterprise infrastructure.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] For example, ABAC can be used at the firewall, server, application, database, and data layer.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The use of attributes bring additional context to evaluate the legitimacy of any request for access and inform the decision to grant or deny access.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] An important consideration when evaluating ABAC solutions is to understand its potential overhead on performance and its impact on the user experience.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] It is expected that the more granular the controls, the higher the overhead.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] ABAC can be used to apply attribute-based, fine-grained authorization to the API methods or functions.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] For instance, a banking API may expose an `approveTransaction(transId)` method.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The API receives the call and authenticates the user.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The PDP retrieves the ABAC policy and necessary attributes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] If the decision is Permit, the underlying API business logic is called.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Otherwise the API returns an error or access denied.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] One of the key benefits to ABAC is that the authorization policies and attributes can be defined in a technology neutral way.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] This means policies defined for APIs or databases can be reused in the application space.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] The same process and flow as the one described in the API section applies here too.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Security for databases has long been specific to the database vendors: Oracle VPD, IBM FGAC, and Microsoft RLS are all means to achieve fine-grained ABAC-like security.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Data security typically goes one step further than database security and applies control directly to the data element.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] This is often referred to as data-centric security.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] On traditional relational databases, ABAC policies can control access to data at the table, column, field, cell and sub-cell using logical controls with filtering conditions and masking based on attributes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Attributes can be data, user, session or tools based to deliver the greatest level of flexibility in dynamically granting/denying access to a specific data element.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] On big data, and distributed file systems such as Hadoop, ABAC applied at the data layer control access to folder, sub-folder, file, sub-file and other granular.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Attribute-based access control can also be applied to Big Data systems like Hadoop.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] Policies similar to those used previously can be applied when retrieving data from data lakes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] As of Windows Server 2012, Microsoft has implemented an ABAC approach to controlling access to files and folders.
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] This is achieved through dynamic access control (DAC) and Security Descriptor Definition Language (SDDL).
[src:aws-lake-formation/attribute-based-access-control] SDDL can be seen as an ABAC language as it uses metadata of the user (claims) and of the file/ folder to control access.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-catalog] A **database catalog** of a database instance consists of metadata in which definitions of database objects such as base tables, views (virtual tables), synonyms, value ranges, indexes, users, and user groups are stored.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-catalog] It is an architecture product that documents the database's content and data quality.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-catalog] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the INFORMATION_SCHEMA, but not all databases follow this, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-catalog] For an example of database-specific metadata access methods, see Oracle metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Data governance involves delegating authority over data and exercising that authority through decision-making processes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] It plays a role in enhancing the value of data assets.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Data governance at the macro level involves regulating cross-border data flows among countries, which is more precisely termed *international data governance*.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] There have been several international groups established by research organizations that aim to grant access to their data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] These groups that enable an exchange of data are, as a result, exposed to domestic and international legal interpretations that ultimately decide how data is used.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] However, as of 2023, there are no international laws or agreements specifically focused on data protection.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Data governance is the set of principles, policies, and processes that guide the effective and responsible use of data within an organization.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] It creates a framework for decision making, accountability, and oversight across the data lifecycle, from creation and storage to sharing and disposal.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Data governance is closely linked with data management, which provides the practical methods to carry out governance objectives.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] These methods include data quality assurance, metadata management, master data management, security controls, and compliance monitoring.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Together, governance and management aim to maximize the value of data as a strategic asset, reduce risks from misuse or inaccuracy, and ensure compliance with regulatory, ethical, and business requirements.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] The importance of this discipline has grown with the rise of big data, cloud computing, and artificial intelligence, where consistent standards and stewardship are essential for privacy protection, interoperability, and informed decision making.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] In 2010, they published a data governance framework based on five components: data principles (which define the data's purpose by an organization), data quality, metadata, data access, and data lifecycle.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] In 2017, the ISO released a framework for data governance, ISO/IEC 38505-1:2017.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Due to the increased use of large language models and the datasets used to train them, a 2022 paper proposed a data governance framework in the context of human rights.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Other well-known data governance frameworks include ISO 8000, the CMMI Data Management Maturity (DMM) Model, and DAMA-DMBOK.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] While data governance initiatives can be driven by a desire to improve data quality, they are often driven by C-level leaders responding to external regulations.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] In a recent report conducted by the CIO WaterCooler community, 54% stated the key driver was efficiencies in processes; 39% - regulatory requirements; and only 7% customer service.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Examples of these regulations include Sarbanes–Oxley Act, Basel I, Basel II, HIPAA, GDPR, cGMP, and a number of data privacy regulations.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] To achieve compliance with these regulations, business processes and controls require formal management processes to govern the data subject to these regulations.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Successful programs identify drivers that are meaningful to both supervisory and executive leadership.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Common themes among the external regulations center on the need to manage risk.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] The risks can be financial misstatement, inadvertent release of sensitive data, or poor data quality for key decisions.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Methods to manage these risks vary from industry to industry.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Examples of commonly referenced best practices and guidelines include COBIT, ISO/IEC 38500, and others.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] The proliferation of regulations and standards creates challenges for data governance professionals, particularly when multiple regulations overlap the data being managed.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Organizations often launch data governance initiatives to address these challenges.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Data governance initiatives improve the quality of data by assigning a team responsible for data's accuracy, completeness, consistency, timeliness, validity, and uniqueness.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] This team usually consists of executive leadership, project management, line-of-business managers, and data stewards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] The team usually employs a methodology for tracking and improving enterprise data, such as Six Sigma, and tools for data mapping, profiling, cleansing, and monitoring data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Many data governance initiatives are also inspired by past attempts to fix information quality at the departmental level, which can lead to incongruent and redundant data quality processes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Most large companies have many applications and databases that can not easily share information.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Therefore, knowledge workers within large organizations may not have access to the data they need to best do their jobs.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] When they do have access to the data, the data quality may be poor.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] By setting up a data governance practice or corporate data authority (individual or area responsible for determining how to proceed, in the best interest of the business, when a data issue arises), these problems can be mitigated.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Implementation of a data governance initiative may vary in scope as well as origin.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Sometimes, an executive mandate will arise to initiate an enterprise-wide effort.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Sometimes the mandate will be to create a pilot project or projects, limited in scope and objectives, aimed at either resolving existing issues or demonstrating value.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Sometimes, an initiative originates from lower down in the organization's hierarchy and will be deployed in a limited scope to demonstrate value to potential sponsors higher up in the organization.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] The initial scope of an implementation can vary greatly as well, from review of a one-off IT system to a cross-organization initiative.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Leaders of successful data governance programs declared at the Data Governance Conference in Orlando, FL, in December 2006, that data governance is about 80 to 95 percent communication.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] That stated, it is a given that many of the objectives of a data governance program must be accomplished with appropriate tools.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Many vendors are now positioning their products as data governance tools.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Due to the different focus areas of various data governance initiatives, a given tool may or may not be appropriate.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-governance] Additionally, many tools that are not marketed as governance tools address governance needs and demands.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:aws-lake-formation/data-lake] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] As such, efforts to define, classify types, or structure metadata are expressed as examples in the context of its use.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" has a history dating to the 1960s where it occurred in computer science and in popular culture.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Different types of metadata serve different functions.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, descriptive metadata for a document might include the author, creation date, file size and keywords.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] It can help users find relevant information and discover resources.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] It can also help organize electronic resources, provide digital identification, and archive and preserve resources.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata allows users to access resources by "allowing resources to be found by relevant criteria, identifying resources, bringing similar resources together, distinguishing dissimilar resources, and giving location information".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata of telecommunication activities including Internet traffic is very widely collected by various national governmental organizations.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This data is used for the purposes of traffic analysis and can be used for mass surveillance.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Unique metadata standards exist for different disciplines (e.g., museum collections, digital audio files, websites, etc.).
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Describing the contents and context of data or data files increases its usefulness.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, a web page may include metadata specifying what software language the page is written in (e.g., HTML), what tools were used to create it, what subjects the page is about, and where to find more information about the subject.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This metadata can automatically improve the reader's experience and make it easier for users to find the web page online.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A CD may include metadata providing information about the musicians, singers, and songwriters whose work appears on the disc.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] In many countries, government organizations routinely store metadata about emails, telephone calls, web pages, video traffic, IP connections, and cell phone locations.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata is not strictly bound to one of these categories, as it can describe a piece of data in many other ways.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] While the metadata application is manifold, covering a large variety of fields, there are specialized and well-accepted models to specify types of metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Bretherton & Singley (1994) distinguish between two distinct classes: structural/control metadata and guide metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes the structure of database objects such as tables, columns, keys and indexes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] *Guide metadata* helps humans find specific items and is usually expressed as a set of keywords in a natural language.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] According to Ralph Kimball, metadata can be divided into three categories: *technical metadata* (or internal metadata), *business metadata* (or external metadata), and *process metadata*.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Business metadata is important because it can greatly facilitate the usefulness of the data to business people.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A simple example of business metadata is a glossary entry.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Hover functionality in an application or web form can enable a glossary definition to be shown when cursor is on a field or term.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Other examples of business metadata include annotation ability within applications.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, a business user may be viewing a business intelligence (BI) report and notice a trend in the data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The user may have background knowledge as to why this trend occurs.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Some business intelligence tools enable the user to create an annotation within the report that explains the trend.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Such an annotation can enhance other users' understanding of the data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This example is especially powerful because it is created by a business user for the use of other business people.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] NISO distinguishes three types of metadata: descriptive, structural, and administrative.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] *Descriptive metadata* is typically used for discovery and identification, as information to search and locate an object, such as title, authors, subjects, keywords, and publisher.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] *Structural metadata* describes how the components of an object are organized.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] An example of structural metadata would be how pages are ordered to form chapters of a book.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Finally, *administrative metadata* gives information to help manage the source.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Administrative metadata refers to the technical information, such as file type, or when and how the file was created.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Two sub-types of administrative metadata are rights management metadata and preservation metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] *Rights management metadata* explains intellectual property rights, while *preservation metadata* contains information to preserve and save a resource.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] An additional type of metadata beginning to be more developed is *accessibility metadata*.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Accessibility metadata is not a new concept to libraries; however, advances in universal design have raised its profile.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Projects like Cloud4All and GPII identified the lack of common terminologies and models to describe the needs and preferences of users and information that fits those needs as a major gap in providing universal access solutions.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Those types of information are accessibility metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The Schema.org website has incorporated several accessibility properties based on IMS Global Access for All Information Model Data Element Specification.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] While the efforts to describe and standardize the varied accessibility needs of information seekers are beginning to become more robust, their adoption into established metadata schemas has not been as developed.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, while Dublin Core (DC)'s "audience" and MARC 21's "reading level" could be used to identify resources suitable for users with dyslexia and DC's "format" could be used to identify resources available in braille, audio, or large print formats, there is more work to be done.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata was traditionally used in the card catalogs of libraries until the 1980s when libraries converted their catalog data to digital databases.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] In the 2000s, as data and information were increasingly stored digitally, this digital data was described using metadata standards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] An early description of "meta data" for computer systems was written by David Griffel and Stuart McIntosh at the MIT Center for International Studies in 1967: "In summary then, we have statements in an object language about subject descriptions of data and token codes for the data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata is defined as the data providing information about one or more aspects of the data; it is used to summarize basic information about data that can make tracking and working with specific data easier.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, a digital image may include metadata that describes the size of the image, its color depth, resolution, when it was created, the shutter speed, and other data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A text document's metadata may contain information about how long the document is, who the author is, when the document was written, and a short summary of the document.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata within web pages can also contain descriptions of page content, as well as key words linked to the content.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] These links are often called "Metatags", which were used as the primary factor in determining order for a web search until the late 1990s.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The reliance on metatags in web searches was decreased in the late 1990s because of "keyword stuffing", whereby metatags were being largely misused to trick search engines into thinking some websites had more relevance in the search than they really did.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata can be stored and managed in a database, often called a metadata registry or metadata repository.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] However, without context and a point of reference, it might be impossible to identify metadata just by looking at it.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example: by itself, a database containing several numbers, all 13 digits long could be the results of calculations or a list of numbers to plug into an equation – without any other context, the numbers themselves can be perceived as the data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] But if given the context that this database is a log of a book collection, those 13-digit numbers may now be identified as ISBNs – information that refers to the book, but is not itself the information within the book.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The term "metadata" was coined in 1968 by Philip Bagley, in his book "Extension of Programming Language Concepts" where it is clear that he uses the term in the ISO 11179 "traditional" sense, which is "structural metadata" i.e.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] "data about the containers of data"; rather than the alternative sense "content about individual instances of data content" or metacontent, the type of data usually found in library catalogs.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Since then the fields of information management, information science, information technology, librarianship, and GIS have widely adopted the term.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] In these fields, the word *metadata* is defined as "data about data".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] While this is the generally accepted definition, various disciplines have adopted their own more specific explanations and uses of the term.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) or, more correctly, the vocabularies used to assemble metadata (metacontent) statements, is typically structured according to a standardized concept using a well-defined metadata scheme, including metadata standards and metadata models.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Tools such as controlled vocabularies, taxonomies, thesauri, data dictionaries, and metadata registries can be used to apply further standardization to the metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Structural metadata commonality is also of paramount importance in data model development and in database design.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata (metacontent) syntax refers to the rules created to structure the fields or elements of metadata (metacontent).
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A single metadata scheme may be expressed in a number of different markup or programming languages, each of which requires a different syntax.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, Dublin Core may be expressed in plain text, HTML, XML, and RDF.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A common example of (guide) metacontent is the bibliographic classification, the subject, the Dewey Decimal class number.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] There is always an implied statement in any "classification" of some object.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] To classify an object as, for example, Dewey class number 514 (Topology) (i.e. books having the number 514 on their spine) the implied statement is: "<book><subject heading><514>".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This is a subject-predicate-object triple, or more importantly, a class-attribute-value triple.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The first 2 elements of the triple (class, attribute) are pieces of some structural metadata having a defined semantic.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The third element is a value, preferably from some controlled vocabulary, some reference (master) data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The combination of the metadata and master data elements results in a statement which is a metacontent statement i.e.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] All of these elements can be thought of as "vocabulary".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Both metadata and master data are vocabularies that can be assembled into metacontent statements.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] There are many sources of these vocabularies, both meta and master data: UML, EDIFACT, XSD, Dewey/UDC/LoC, SKOS, ISO-25964, Pantone, Linnaean Binomial Nomenclature, etc.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The process indexes pages and then matches text strings using its complex algorithm; there is no intelligence or "inferencing" occurring, just the illusion thereof.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can be hierarchical in nature where relationships exist between metadata elements and elements are nested so that parent-child relationships exist between the elements.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] An example of a hierarchical metadata schema is the IEEE LOM schema, in which metadata elements may belong to a parent metadata element.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata can also be one-dimensional, or linear, where each element is completely discrete from other elements and classified according to one dimension only.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] An example of a linear metadata schema is the Dublin Core schema, which is one-dimensional.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata schemata are often 2 dimensional, or planar, where each element is completely discrete from other elements but classified according to 2 orthogonal dimensions.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The degree to which the data or metadata is structured is referred to as "granularity".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] "Granularity" refers to how much detail is provided.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata with a high granularity allows for deeper, more detailed, and more structured information and enables a greater level of technical manipulation.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A lower level of granularity means that metadata can be created for considerably lower costs but will not provide as detailed information.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The major impact of granularity is not only on creation and capture, but moreover on maintenance costs.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] As soon as the metadata structures become outdated, so too is the access to the referred data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Hence granularity must take into account the effort to create the metadata as well as the effort to maintain it.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] In all cases where the metadata schemata exceed the planar depiction, some type of hypermapping is required to enable display and view of metadata according to chosen aspect and to serve special views.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Hypermapping frequently applies to layering of geographical and geological information overlays.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] International standards apply to metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Much work is being accomplished in the national and international standards communities, especially ANSI (American National Standards Institute) and ISO (International Organization for Standardization) to reach a consensus on standardizing metadata and registries.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The core metadata registry standard is ISO/IEC 11179 Metadata Registries (MDR), the framework for the standard is described in ISO/IEC 11179-1:2004.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] A new edition of Part 1 is in its final stage for publication in 2015 or early 2016.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] It has been revised to align with the current edition of Part 3, ISO/IEC 11179-3:2013 which extends the MDR to support the registration of Concept Systems.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This standard specifies a schema for recording both the meaning and technical structure of the data for unambiguous usage by humans and computers.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 standard refers to metadata as information objects about data, or "data about data".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] In ISO/IEC 11179 Part-3, the information objects are data about Data Elements, Value Domains, and other reusable semantic and representational information objects that describe the meaning and technical details of a data item.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This standard also prescribes the details for a metadata registry, and for registering and administering the information objects within a Metadata Registry.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] ISO/IEC 11179 Part 3 also has provisions for describing compound structures that are derivations of other data elements, for example through calculations, collections of one or more data elements, or other forms of derived data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This standard has become the general basis for other kinds of metadata registries, reusing and extending the registration and administration portion of the standard.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The Geospatial community has a tradition of specialized geospatial metadata standards, particularly building on traditions of map- and image-libraries and catalogs.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Formal metadata is usually essential for geospatial data, as common text-processing approaches are not applicable.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The Dublin Core metadata terms are a set of vocabulary terms that can be used to describe resources for the purposes of discovery.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The W3C Data Catalog Vocabulary (DCAT) is an RDF vocabulary that supplements Dublin Core with classes for Dataset, Data Service, Catalog, and Catalog Record.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] DCAT also uses elements from FOAF, PROV-O, and OWL-Time.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] DCAT provides an RDF model to support the typical structure of a catalog that contains records, each describing a dataset or service.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Although not a standard, Microformat (also mentioned in the section metadata on the internet below) is a web-based approach to semantic markup which seeks to re-use existing HTML/XHTML tags to convey metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Microformat follows XHTML and HTML standards but is not a standard in itself.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] In metadata, Naming and Design Rules are a set of guidelines and naming conventions that go beyond what a single data exchange standard specification will permit.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] The most common standard that Naming and Design Rules are created on is XML Schema.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] For example, the use of upper camel case data element names is a convention used in many standard but is not specified by the XML Schema specification.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Naming and Design Rules have become an important aspect of each organizations data exchange standards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Within the United States, Naming and Design Rules standards are recommended for each federal and state agency.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Most common types of computer files can embed metadata, including documents, (e.g.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Microsoft Office files, OpenDocument files, PDF) images, (e.g.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata may be added to files by users, but some metadata is often automatically added to files by authoring applications or by devices used to produce the files, without user intervention.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] While metadata in files are useful for finding them, they can be a privacy hazard when the files are shared.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Using metadata removal tools to clean files before sharing them can mitigate this risk.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Some metadata is created by the camera such as, color space, color channels, exposure time, and aperture (EXIF), while some is input by the photographer and/or software after downloading to a computer.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Most digital cameras write metadata about the model number, shutter speed, etc., and some enable you to edit it; this functionality has been available on most Nikon DSLRs since the Nikon D3, on most new Canon cameras since the Canon EOS 7D, and on most Pentax DSLRs since the Pentax K-3.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata can be used to make organizing in post-production easier with the use of key-wording.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Filters can be used to analyze a specific set of photographs and create selections on criteria like rating or capture time.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] On devices with geolocation capabilities like GPS (smartphones in particular), the location the photo was taken from may also be included.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Photographic Metadata Standards are governed by organizations that develop the following standards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata is particularly useful in video, where information about its contents (such as transcripts of conversations and text descriptions of its scenes) is not directly understandable by a computer, but where an efficient search of the content is desirable.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] This is particularly useful in video applications such as Automatic Number Plate Recognition and Vehicle Recognition Identification software, wherein license plate data is saved and used to create reports and alerts.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Avid's MetaSync and Adobe's Bridge are examples of professional video editing software with access to metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Various file systems are utilising metadata, such as FAT32 and NTFS.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Information on the times, origins and destinations of phone calls, electronic messages, instant messages, and other modes of telecommunication, as opposed to message content, is another form of metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Geospatial metadata relates to Geographic Information Systems (GIS) files, maps, images, and other data that is location-based.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] Metadata is used in GIS to document the characteristics and attributes of geographic data, such as database files and data that is developed within a GIS.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p01] It includes details like who developed the data, when it was collected, how it was processed, and what formats it's available in, and then delivers the context for the data to be used effectively.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata can be created either by automated information processing or by manual work.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Elementary metadata captured by computers can include information about when an object was created, who created it, when it was last updated, file size, and file extension.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] A metadata engine collects, stores and analyzes information about data and metadata in use within a domain.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Data virtualization emerged in the 2000s as the new software technology to complete the virtualization "stack" in the enterprise.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata is used in data virtualization servers which are enterprise infrastructure components, alongside database and application servers.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata in these servers is saved as persistent repository and describe business objects in various enterprise systems and applications.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Structural metadata commonality is also important to support data virtualization.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Standardization and harmonization work has brought advantages to industry efforts to build metadata systems in the statistical community.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Several metadata guidelines and standards such as the European Statistics Code of Practice and ISO 17369:2013 (Statistical Data and Metadata Exchange or SDMX) provide key principles for how businesses, government bodies, and other entities should manage statistical data and metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Entities such as Eurostat, European System of Central Banks, and the U.S.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Environmental Protection Agency have implemented these and other such standards and guidelines with the goal of improving "efficiency when managing statistical business processes".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata has been used in various ways as a means of cataloging items in libraries in both digital and analog formats.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Such data helps classify, aggregate, identify, and locate a particular book, DVD, magazine, or any object a library might hold in its collection.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Until the 1980s, many library catalogs used 3x5 inch cards in file drawers to display a book's title, author, subject matter, and an abbreviated alpha-numeric string (call number) which indicated the physical location of the book within the library's shelves.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The Dewey Decimal System employed by libraries for the classification of library materials by subject is an early example of metadata usage.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The early paper catalog had information regarding whichever item was described on said card: title, author, subject, and a number as to where to find said item.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Beginning in the 1980s and 1990s, many libraries replaced these paper file cards with computer databases.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] These computer databases make it much easier and faster for users to do keyword searches.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Another form of older metadata collection is the use by the US Census Bureau of what is known as the "Long Form".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The Long Form asks questions that are used to create demographic data to find patterns of distribution.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Libraries employ metadata in library catalogues, most commonly as part of an Integrated Library Management System.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata is obtained by cataloging resources such as books, periodicals, DVDs, web pages or digital images.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This data is stored in the integrated library management system, ILMS, using the MARC metadata standard.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The purpose is to direct patrons to the physical or electronic location of items or areas they seek as well as to provide a description of the item/s in question.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] More recent and specialized instances of library metadata include the establishment of digital libraries including e-print repositories and digital image libraries.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] While often based on library principles, the focus on non-librarian use, especially in providing metadata, means they do not follow traditional or common cataloging approaches.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Given the custom nature of included materials, metadata fields are often specially created e.g. taxonomic classification fields, location fields, keywords, or copyright statement.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Standard file information such as file size and format are usually automatically included.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Library operation has for decades been a key topic in efforts toward international standardization.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Standards for metadata in digital libraries include Dublin Core, METS, MODS, DDI, DOI, URN, PREMIS schema, EML, and OAI-PMH.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Leading libraries in the world give hints on their metadata standards strategies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] A similar concept is the synset, short for *synonym set*, a group of one or more synonyms that share a common meaning in some context.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Synsets are a fundamental concept in computational linguistics and lexical semantics, most notably used in the WordNet lexical database of English.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The concept has been extended to other languages and multilingual projects such as EuroWordNet, BabelNet, and the Global WordNet initiative.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata for scientific publications is often created by journal publishers and citation databases such as PubMed and Web of Science.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The data contained within manuscripts or accompanying them as supplementary material is less often subject to metadata creation, though they may be submitted to e.g. biomedical databases after publication.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The original authors and database curators then become responsible for metadata creation, with the assistance of automated processes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Comprehensive metadata for all experimental data is the foundation of the FAIR Guiding Principles, or the standards for ensuring research data are findable, accessible, interoperable, and reusable.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Such metadata can then be utilized, complemented, and made accessible in useful ways.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] OpenAlex is a free online index of over 200 million scientific documents that integrates and provides metadata such as sources, citations, author information, scientific fields, and research topics.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Its API and open source website can be used for metascience, scientometrics, and novel tools that query this semantic web of papers.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Another project under development, Scholia, uses the metadata of scientific publications for various visualizations and aggregation features such as providing a simple user interface summarizing literature about a specific feature of the SARS-CoV-2 virus using Wikidata's "main subject" property.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In research labor, transparent metadata about authors' contributions to works have been proposed – e.g. the role played in the production of the paper, the level of contribution and the responsibilities.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Moreover, various metadata about scientific outputs can be created or complemented – for instance, some organizations attempt to track and link citations of papers as 'Supporting', 'Mentioning' or 'Contrasting' the study.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata in a museum context is the information that trained cultural documentation specialists, such as archivists, librarians, museum registrars and curators, create to index, structure, describe, identify, or otherwise specify works of art, architecture, cultural objects and their images.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Descriptive metadata is most commonly used in museum contexts for object identification and resource recovery purposes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Many museums and cultural heritage centers recognize that given the diversity of artworks and cultural objects, no single model or standard suffices to describe and catalog cultural works.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] For example, a sculpted Indigenous artifact could be classified as an artwork, an archaeological artifact, or an Indigenous heritage item.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] These standards use HTML and XML markup languages for machine processing, publication and implementation.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The Anglo-American Cataloguing Rules (AACR), originally developed for characterizing books, have also been applied to cultural objects, works of art and architecture.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Standards, such as the CCO, are integrated within a Museum's Collections Management System (CMS), a database through which museums are able to manage their collections, acquisitions, loans and conservation.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Scholars and professionals in the field note that the "quickly evolving landscape of standards and technologies" creates challenges for cultural documentarians, specifically non-technically trained professionals.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Most collecting institutions and museums use a relational database to categorize cultural works and their images.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Relational databases and metadata work to document and describe the complex relationships amongst cultural objects and multi-faceted works of art, as well as between objects and places, people, and artistic movements.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Relational database structures are also beneficial within collecting institutions and museums because they allow for archivists to make a clear distinction between cultural objects and their images; an unclear distinction could lead to confusing and inaccurate searches.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The established institutional cataloging practices, goals, and expertise of cultural documentarians and database structure also influence the information ascribed to cultural objects and the ways in which cultural objects are categorized.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Additionally, museums often employ standardized commercial collection management software that prescribes and limits the ways in which archivists can describe artworks and cultural objects.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] As well, collecting institutions and museums use Controlled Vocabularies to describe cultural objects and artworks in their collections.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Getty Vocabularies and the Library of Congress Controlled Vocabularies are reputable within the museum community and are recommended by CCO standards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Museums are encouraged to use controlled vocabularies that are contextual and relevant to their collections and enhance the functionality of their digital information systems.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Controlled Vocabularies are beneficial within databases because they provide a high level of consistency, improving resource retrieval.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata structures, including controlled vocabularies, reflect the ontologies of the systems from which they were created.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Often the processes through which cultural objects are described and categorized through metadata in museums do not reflect the perspectives of the maker communities.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata has been instrumental in the creation of digital information systems and archives within museums and has made it easier for museums to publish digital content online.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This has enabled audiences who might not have had access to cultural objects due to geographic or economic barriers to have access to them.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In the 2000s, as more museums have adopted archival standards and created intricate databases, discussions about Linked Data between museum databases have come up in the museum, archival, and library science communities.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Collection Management Systems (CMS) and Digital Asset Management tools can be local or shared systems.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Digital Humanities scholars note many benefits of interoperability between museum databases and collections, while also acknowledging the difficulties of achieving such interoperability.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Problems involving metadata in litigation in the United States are becoming widespread.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Courts have looked at various questions involving metadata, including the discoverability of metadata by parties.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The Federal Rules of Civil Procedure have specific rules for discovery of electronically stored information, and subsequent case law applying those rules has elucidated on the litigant's duty to produce metadata when litigating in federal court.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In October 2009, the Arizona Supreme Court has ruled that metadata records are public record.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Document metadata have proven particularly important in legal environments in which litigation has requested metadata, that can include sensitive information detrimental to a certain party in court.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Using metadata removal tools to "clean" or redact documents can mitigate the risks of unwittingly sending sensitive data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This process partially (see data remanence) protects law firms from potentially damaging leaking of sensitive data through electronic discovery.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Opinion polls have shown that 45% of Americans are "not at all confident" in the ability of social media sites to ensure their personal data is secure and 40% say that social media sites should not be able to store any information on individuals.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] 76% of Americans say that they are not confident that the information advertising agencies collect on them is secure and 50% say that online advertising agencies should not be allowed to record any of their information at all.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In the EU, the Snowden disclosures have been influential in its review of matters concerning privacy and the processing of personal data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] As of 2025, of the 18 European countries surveyed by the Data Retention Directive, only Germany, the Netherlands and Romania do not have any data retention rules in force.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] On 6 October 2020, the Court of Justice for the European Union (CJEU) ruled that indiscriminate mass data retention schemes are illegal under EU law.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] With France passing a law on 18 December 2013 that facilitates the collection of data by the French military and intelligence services.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] While in April 2022 the Portuguese Constitutional Court declared unconstitutional the CJEU laws on the retention of data generated or processed in connection with the provision of publicly available electronic communications services or of public communications networks.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In Australia, the need to strengthen national security has resulted in the introduction of a new metadata storage law.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This new law means that both security and policing agencies will be allowed to access up to 2 years of an individual's metadata, with the aim of making it easier to stop any terrorist attacks and serious crimes from happening.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Legislative metadata has been discussed in various forums, such as workshops held by the Legal Information Institute at the Cornell Law School on 22 and 23 March 2010.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The documentation for these workshops is titled "Suggested metadata practices for legislation and regulations".
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Australian medical research pioneered the definition of metadata for applications in health care.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] That approach offers the first recognized attempt to adhere to international standards in medical sciences instead of defining a proprietary standard under the World Health Organization (WHO) umbrella.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The medical community yet did not approve of the need to follow metadata standards despite research that supported these standards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Research studies in the fields of biomedicine and molecular biology frequently yield large quantities of data, including results of genome or meta-genome sequencing, proteomics data, and even notes or plans created during the course of research itself.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Each data type involves its own variety of metadata and the processes necessary to produce these metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] General metadata standards, such as ISA-Tab, allow researchers to create and exchange experimental metadata in consistent formats.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Specific experimental approaches frequently have their own metadata standards and systems: metadata standards for mass spectrometry include mzML and SPLASH, while XML-based standards such as PDBML and SRA XML serve as standards for macromolecular structure and sequencing data, respectively.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The products of biomedical research are generally realized as peer-reviewed manuscripts and these publications are yet another source of data .
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] A data warehouse (DW) is a repository of an organization's electronically stored data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Data warehouses are designed to manage and store the data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Data warehouses differ from business intelligence (BI) systems because BI systems are designed to use data to create reports and analyze the information, to provide strategic guidance to management.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata is an important tool in how data is stored in data warehouses.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The purpose of a data warehouse is to house standardized, structured, consistent, integrated, correct, "cleaned" and timely data, extracted from various operational systems in an organization.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The extracted data are integrated in the data warehouse environment to provide an enterprise-wide perspective.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Data are structured in a way to serve the reporting and analytic requirements.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The design of structural metadata commonality using a data modeling method such as entity-relationship model diagramming is important in any data warehouse development effort.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] They detail metadata on each piece of data in the data warehouse.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] An essential component of a data warehouse/business intelligence system is the metadata and tools to manage and retrieve the metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Ralph Kimball describes metadata as the DNA of the data warehouse as metadata defines the elements of the data warehouse and how they work together.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Kimball et al. refer to three main categories of metadata: technical, business and process.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Technical metadata is primarily definitional, while business metadata and process metadata are primarily descriptive.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The HTML format used to define web pages allows for the inclusion of a variety of types of metadata, from basic descriptive text, dates and keywords to further advanced metadata schemes such as the Dublin Core, e-GMS, and AGLS standards.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Pages and files can also be geotagged with coordinates, categorized or tagged, including collaboratively such as with folksonomies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] When media has identifiers set or when such can be generated, information such as file tags and descriptions can be pulled or scraped from the Internet – for example about movies.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Various online databases are aggregated and provide metadata for various data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The collaboratively built Wikidata has identifiers not just for media but also abstract concepts, various objects, and other entities, that can be looked up by humans and machines to retrieve useful information and to link knowledge in other knowledge bases and databases.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata may be included in the page's header or in a separate file.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Microformats allow metadata to be added to on-page data in a way that regular web users do not see, but computers, web crawlers and search engines can readily access.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Many search engines are cautious about using metadata in their ranking algorithms because of exploitation of metadata and the practice of search engine optimization, SEO, to improve rankings.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] See the Meta element article for further discussion.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This cautious attitude may be justified as people, according to Doctorow, are not executing care and diligence when creating their own metadata and that metadata is part of a competitive environment where the metadata is used to promote the metadata creators own purposes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Studies show that search engines respond to web pages with metadata implementations, and Google has an announcement on its site showing the meta tags that its search engine understands.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Enterprise search startup Swiftype recognizes metadata as a relevance signal that webmasters can implement for their website-specific search engine, even releasing their own extension, known as Meta Tags 2.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This metadata can be linked to the video media thanks to the video servers.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Most major broadcast sporting events like FIFA World Cup or the Olympic Games use this metadata to distribute their video content to TV stations through keywords.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] It is often the host broadcaster who is in charge of organizing metadata through its *International Broadcast Centre* and its video servers.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This metadata is recorded with the images and entered by metadata operators (*loggers*) who associate in live metadata available in *metadata grids* through software (such as Multicam(LSM) or IPDirector used during the FIFA World Cup or Olympic Games).
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Ecological and environmental metadata is intended to document the "who, what, when, where, why, and how" of data collection for a particular study.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] This typically means which organization or institution collected the data, what type of data, which date(s) the data was collected, the rationale for the data collection, and the methodology used for the data collection.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata should be generated in a format commonly used by the most relevant science community, such as Darwin Core, Ecological Metadata Language, or Dublin Core.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata editing tools exist to facilitate metadata generation (e.g.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata should describe the provenance of the data (where they originated, as well as any transformations the data underwent) and how to give credit for (cite) the data products.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] When first released in 1982, Compact Discs only contained a Table Of Contents (TOC) with the number of tracks on the disc and their length in samples.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Fourteen years later in 1996, a revision of the CD Red Book standard added CD-Text to carry additional metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Shortly thereafter, it became common for personal computers to retrieve metadata from external sources (e.g.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Digital audio formats such as digital audio files superseded music formats such as cassette tapes and CDs in the 2000s.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Digital audio files could be labeled with more information than could be contained in just the file name.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] That descriptive information is called the **audio tag** or audio metadata in general.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Computer programs specializing in adding or modifying this information are called tag editors.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata can be used to name, describe, catalog, and indicate ownership or copyright for a digital audio file, and its presence makes it much easier to locate a specific audio file within a group, typically through use of a search engine that accesses the metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] As different digital audio formats were developed, attempts were made to standardize a specific location within the digital files where this information could be stored.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] As a result, almost all digital audio formats, including mp3, broadcast wav, and AIFF files, have similar standardized locations that can be populated with metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The metadata for compressed and uncompressed digital music is often encoded in the ID3 tag.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Common editors such as TagLib support MP3, Ogg Vorbis, FLAC, MPC, Speex, WavPack TrueAudio, WAV, AIFF, MP4, and ASF file formats.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] With the availability of cloud applications, which include those to add metadata to content, metadata is increasingly available over the Internet.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored either *internally*, in the same file or structure as the data (this is also called *embedded metadata*), or *externally*, in a separate file or field from the described data.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] A data repository typically stores the metadata *detached* from the data but can be designed to support embedded metadata approaches.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata can be stored in either human-readable or binary form.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Storing metadata in a human-readable format such as XML can be useful because users can understand and edit it without specialized tools.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] However, text-based formats are rarely optimized for storage capacity, communication time, or processing speed.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] A binary metadata format enables efficiency in all these respects, but requires special software to convert the binary information into human-readable content.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Each relational database system has its own mechanisms for storing metadata.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In database terminology, this set of metadata is referred to as the catalog.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The SQL standard specifies a uniform means to access the catalog, called the information schema, but not all databases implement it, even if they implement other aspects of the SQL standard.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Programmatic access to metadata is possible using APIs such as JDBC, or SchemaCrawler.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] One of the first satirical examinations of the concept of Metadata as we understand it today is American science fiction author Hal Draper's short story, "MS Fnd in a Lbry" (1961).
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Here, the knowledge of all Mankind is condensed into an object the size of a desk drawer, however, the magnitude of the metadata (e.g. catalog of catalogs of... , as well as indexes and histories) eventually leads to dire yet humorous consequences for the human race.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] The story prefigures the modern consequences of allowing metadata to become more important than the real data it is concerned with, and the risks inherent in that eventuality as a cautionary tale.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Documentation refers to all contextual information that explains and describes a dataset, system, or research process to ensure it is understandable, usable, and reusable.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] It covers broad details such as the study background, data collection methods, file inventories, codebooks, data dictionaries, user guides, and workflow notes.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] In contrast, metadata is a specific and highly structured form of documentation that provides standardized information about the data itself—such as the title, creator, file format, size, access conditions, and how files or sections are organized.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Metadata and documentation are therefore related but distinct concepts in information management.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] Both play crucial roles in data governance, usability, and preservation.
[src:aws-lake-formation/metadata-p02] While documentation gives the full narrative and instructions surrounding the data, metadata offers concise, structured descriptors that help users and systems identify, locate, manage and preserve the data efficiently.
